40|$|This thesis {{describes}} how <b>Virtual</b> <b>Reality</b> technology (<b>VR)</b> {{can be used}} as a tool in traffic simulation. The purpose of this work has been to explore the possibilities of developing a basic prototype for simulation of real traffic situations. During the process a framework of useful features for creating and controlling autonomous actors in a virtual environment has been established. Possible models of communication between such actors and their ability to interact in real traffic situations have also been explored. These ideas have been implemented on an already existing simulation platform and applied to a purpose-designed model. Evaluation of the result has been conducted in form of interviews with representatives from a hypothetical target audience. Their thoughts and opinions have provided valuable information about future augmentation and improvement of the concept. Sammanfattning Denna avhandling beskriver hur <b>Virtual</b> <b>Reality</b> teknik (<b>VR)</b> kan anvÃ¤ndas som ett verktyg vid trafiksimulering. Syftet med arbetet har varit att utforska mÃ¶jligheterna fÃ¶r att utveckla en enkel prototyp fÃ¶r simulering av realistiska trafiksituationer. Unde...|$|R
40|$|<b>Virtual</b> <b>reality</b> {{scenarios}} are restricted, from a psychological point of view, to the feedback from arbitrary motor responses which are measured with data gloves or suits. However, this only represents {{one section of}} human behaviour. This project intends to export physiological parameters for emotions into a virtual world. As a representation for emotions, visualizations of biosignals, such as breathing rhythm, are used. In the preoccupation with the subject of virtual emotions, one is confronted with unusual perspectives concerning communications and cognitive sciences. In addition to this, there are references to psychotherapeutical techniques of trance induction. <b>VIRTUAL</b> <b>REALITY</b> WITHOUT EMOTIONS? <b>Virtual</b> <b>realities</b> (<b>VR)</b> have {{a high degree of}} stimulation because of the transformation possibilities of its actors. Scenarios of transformation are possible with future technologies, in which data travellers can assume any appearance in order to play a role they have thought out. However, if we compare the complexity of VR with our everyday environment, great shortcomings become apparent. On account of the afore-mentioned fact that VR is restricted to arbitrary motor responses, only an extremely limited behaviour is possible. Thi...|$|R
